  "why": "The paper provides diagnostic analysis that characterizes properties of discovered failures and how they correlate with input structure and defenses, but it does not trace failures to deeper underlying model vulnerabilities (e.g., corrupted training data, spurious features, or internal neuron behavior). Specifically, the authors analyze why a prior token-level method (GCG) fails under defenses (perplexity and paraphrasing) and why AutoDAN succeeds, linking these outcomes to the semantic meaningfulness of generated prompts and to overfitting from gradient/token-level optimization. This constitutes partial diagnostic insight (correlations between failure/success and prompt properties and defenses) rather than a full causal attribution to underlying model vulnerabilities or internal model signals.",
  "evidence": "Page 2, Introduction / Motivation: \"...they often generate jailbreak prompts composed of nonsensical sequences or gibberish, i.e., without any semantic meaning... This severe flaw makes them highly susceptible to naive defense mechanisms like perplexity-based detection.\" (p.2, para beginning \"However, there are two limitations...\")\n\nPage 7-8, Results / Effectiveness against defense: \"...the perplexity defense significantly undermines the effectiveness of the token-level jailbreak attack, i.e., GCG attack. However, the semantically meaningful jailbreak prompts AutoDAN (and the original handcrafted DAN) is not influenced. These findings underscore the capability of our method to generate semantically meaningful content similar to benign text, verifying the stealthiness of our method.\" (Sec. 4.2, \"Effectiveness against defense\")\n\nPage 8, Transferability discussion (Table 2 caption / text): \"We hypothesize that this is because the AutoDAN generates prompts at a semantic level without relying on direct guidance from gradient information on the tokens, thereby avoiding overfitting on white-box models.\" (Sec. 4.2, \"Transferability\")\n\nAppendix I / Ablation (paraphrasing defense): \"A major difference is the performance of both attacks when facing the paraphrasing defense, where GCG becomes invalid, but AutoDAN retains its effectiveness on many samples. We take a further investigation and find that the paraphrasing usually 'discards' the GCG’s suffixes as they are usually garbled characters. However, the jailbreak prompts generated by AutoDAN maintain their meaning after paraphrasing...\" (Appendix I, final paragraph / Table 11)"
